data.content:
Replace `[ExpectedException]` with `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>`, which lets you also inspect the exception:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()
{
    var service = new UserService();

    var ex = Assert.ThrowsExactly<ArgumentNullException>(
        () => service.CreateUser(null, "John"));

    Assert.AreEqual("email", ex.ParamName); // optional: verify details
}
```

**Why this is better:**

| `[ExpectedException]` | `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>` |
|---|---|
| Any line can throw — masks bugs | Only the specific call is checked |
| Can't inspect the exception | Returns the exception for further assertions |
| Obsolete pattern | Modern MSTest 3.x+ API |

Use `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>` for exact type matching, or `Assert.Throws<T>` if derived exception types should also pass. For async methods, use `Assert.ThrowsExactlyAsync<T>`.
